org.xtext.xrobot.api

Class Vector

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.xtext.xrobot.api.Vector

  • public class Vector
extends java.lang.Object
    A vector in a two-dimensional space. Vectors can be defined with Cartesian coordinates x and y or with polar coordinates length and angle. There is a static construction method for each of these definitions. Regardless of how a vector has been defined, all four values are always available. For example, the expression 
    Vector.cartesian(10, 10).getAngle()
    yields the value 45°, and 
    Vector.polar(10, 180).getX()
    yields the value -10.

    Cartesian coordinates (x, y) as well as the length are in centimeters (for positions) or in centimeters per second (for speeds), while the angle is in degrees. Angles are always normalized to the range from -180° to +180° using GeometryExtensions.minimizeAngle(double).

      • getLength

        public double getLength()
        Return the length of the vector in centimeters (for positions) or centimeters per second (for speeds). The meaning of this value depends on how the vector is used:
        • If this represents an absolute position, the length corresponds to the distance to the center of the arena.
        • If this represents a relative position, the length corresponds to the distance between the two compared points.
        • If this represents a speed, the length corresponds to the absolute speed value.
        Returns:
        the length of this vector

      • getAngle

        public double getAngle()
        Return the angle of the vector in degrees in the range from -180° to +180°. The angle is interpreted mathematically, that means a vector with angle 0 points to the right and increasing the angle corresponds to a counter-clockwise rotation.
        Returns:
        the angle of this vector
